answers.body_markdown:
Time complexity analysis is usually performed in `O` (_big O_).

If you have a simple loop that iterates over a collection of _n_ entries, the time complexity will be `O(n)`.
If that loop skips saome items, the time complexity in terms of `O` will be the same. For certain purposes (not this one), you can also introduce the concept of _average_, _max_ and _min_.

Your code,

```java
public static void main(String[] args) 
{
    int n = 39;
    for(int i = 0; i&lt;n; i++)
    {
        for(int j = 1; i&lt;i*i; i++)
        {
            for(int k = 3; k&lt;j; k = k*2)
            {
                    
            }
        }
    }
}
```

has 3 loops:
- loop 1: iterates on a collection of `n` elements, thus the loop is in `O(n)`.
- loop 2: here the for cycle is non canonical. The condition `i &lt; i * i` is always true except for 0, therefore this program does not terminate in theory.

_From a theoretical point of view, this time complexity cannot be determined, since your code does not halt._

What follows is a speculation for practical purposes.
If you consider that practically, we use arithemetic without overflow checks, _loop 2_ will terminate sooner or later depending on the size of an integer (assuming 32 bit). The condition `i*i` is false for `i=46341`.

Loop 3 is never executed because of the condition is always false. So the time complexity of your code is constant on `p` where `p` is the first greatest machine number where the expression `p*p` overflows.

